Luciano Bernardino da Costa

In Mediterranean Area, the interest in geography and maps that had begun in the 2ⁿᵈ century with the Greco-Roman scholar Klaudios Ptolemaios increasingly grew in later periods and unique collections of maps of the 15th and 16th century were assembled in museums, palaces and private collections. In these centuries, Mediterranean was common area of observation, study and science for Latin and Turkish seamen and cartographer. Tunuslu İbrâhim Kâtibî (Ibrahim Katibi of Tunis), Mürsiyeli İbrâhim (Ibrahim of Murcia), El-Hacc Ebu’l Hasan, Gabriel Devallsecha, Jacobus Russus of Messina, Giorgio Sideri (Callapoda Da Candia) and other seamen / cartographers drew maps and portolans. These portolans provides us with the geographical properties of the Mediterranean coasts, information on the cities and the life of people. They represent of interaction between Ottoman and Latin artists who had the important values of Mediterranean arts too. The present paper aims to study the below portolans: 
A- Portolans drawn by Ottoman cartographers: 
Mediterranean Portolan (1413-14) of Tunuslu İbrâhim Kâtibî (Ibrahim Katibi of Tunis); 
Mediterranean Portolan (1461) of Mürsiyeli İbrâhim (Ibrahim of Murcia); 
Mediterranean Portolan (1570?) of El-Hacc Ebu’l Hasan.  
B- Portolans drawn by Latin cartographers: 
Mediterranean Portolan (1447) of Gabriel Devallsecha;  
Mediterranean Portolan (1533) of Jacobus Russus of Messina; 
Mediterranean Portolan (1565) of Giorgio Sideri (Callapoda Da Candia).
